<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-819-696  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 819 696.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Expert  August 1990 v5 n4 p29(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Knowledge specification of an expert system. (includes relatedarticle on conceptual-structure theory) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Slagle, James R.; Gardiner, David a.; Han, Kyungsook.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A practical and disciplined methodology for expert systemdevelopment is needed.andP;  One method is to use knowledgespecifications as a base for developing and maintaining expertsystems, especially medium- to large-scale systems with severaldevelopers and users who are not developers.andP;  Knowledgespecifications are another step in moving the boundary betweenhumans and intelligent computers.andP;  Conceptual structures are usedas the specification language; features include a clear mapping tonatural language so communication with nontechnical people iseasy; mapping to logic; sectional-constraint mechanism; typedefinition mechanism for reasoning on different levels; andmechanism to incorporate background knowledge and hypothesis.andP;  Themethodology uses six types of conceptual structures: typedefinitions, schemata with and without actors, implications,facts, a type lattice, and canonical graphs.andP;  These can beproduced from protocols by identifying: key concepts, lines ofreasoning, facts, relations among concepts, and constraints ofconcepts and relations.andP;  Knowledge specification reduces the costof developing an expert system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Expert SystemsResearch and DevelopmentMethodsMaintenance.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Expert system development approaches. (chart)Relationships among problem, knowledge, program, and hardware.andO;(chart)Going-concern issues and cues. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>